            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "I tried to retrieve sales records from your Fabric workspace but the data source isn’t available right now, so I can’t show your actual records at the moment. I can still explain what “sales records” usually are, what they commonly contain, and how they’re used — and I can help further when the data source is available or if you provide a sample.\n\nQuick summary (what sales records are)\n- A sales record is a stored record of a transaction (or sale) between a seller and buyer. They are used for revenue tracking, reporting, forecasting, customer insights, and accounting.\n\nTypical fields in a sales-record dataset\n- transaction_id (unique)\n- transaction_date / timestamp\n- customer_id (and customer metadata: name, segment, region)\n- product_id / sku (and product metadata)\n- quantity\n- unit_price\n- discount_amount / discount_pct\n- tax_amount\n- shipping_cost\n- total_amount (net and gross)\n- payment_method / status\n- sales_rep / channel (online, retail, partner)\n- order_status (completed, refunded, canceled)\n- invoice_id, return_reason (if applicable)\n\nCommon KPIs and analyses\n- Revenue (total, by period, by product, by region)\n- Units sold / volume\n- Average order value (AOV)\n- Gross margin and profit\n- Sales growth (YoY, MoM)\n- Refund / return rate\n- Customer lifetime value (CLV)\n- Repeat purchase rate / retention\n- Sales per channel / sales per rep\n- Forecasting and trend analysis\n\nData quality and governance considerations\n- Ensure unique transaction IDs and consistent timestamp formats.\n- Normalize product and customer identifiers to avoid duplicates.\n- Validate totals (unit_price*quantity + tax + shipping - discount = total).\n- Track provenance and transformations for audibility.\n- Define retention policies, backups, and archival strategy.\n\nStorage, tooling and reporting\n- Storage: relational DBs (Postgres, SQL Server), data warehouses (Snowflake, Synapse), or transactional stores depending on volume and access needs.\n- ETL/ELT: pipelines to transform incoming orders into analytics-ready tables.\n- BI & dashboards: revenue dashboards, cohort analysis, and pivot reports (Power BI, Tableau).\n- Real-time needs: streaming ingestion if you require near-real-time dashboards.\n\nSecurity & compliance\n- Limit PII exposure; encrypt sensitive fields (payment info).\n- Comply with regulations (PCI-DSS for payments, GDPR for customer data).\n- Role-based access controls for analytics and raw data.\n\nNext steps I can take for you\n- Retry fetching the sales dataset from Fabric when the data source is available.\n- If you name the dataset/table or provide a sample CSV, I can analyze it (summary stats, top products, trends, anomalies).\n- Build sample queries, dashboard wireframes, or KPI definitions tailored to your business.\n\nWhich would you like next — retry the Fabric fetch, share the dataset name, or provide a sample so I can analyze it for you?",
